   367ŌåÆ    format: str,
   368ŌåÆ) -> tuple[float, float]:
   369ŌåÆ    """Divide `value` by `divisor`, returning the quotient and remainder.
   370ŌåÆ
   371ŌåÆ    If `unit` is `minimum_unit`, the quotient will be the rounding of `value / divisor`
   372ŌåÆ    according to the `format` string and the remainder will be zero. The rationale is
   373ŌåÆ    that if `unit` is the unit of the quotient, we cannot represent the remainder
   374ŌåÆ    because it would require a unit smaller than the `minimum_unit`.
   375ŌåÆ
   376ŌåÆ    >>> from humanize.time import _quotient_and_remainder, Unit
   377ŌåÆ    >>> _quotient_and_remainder(36, 24, Unit.DAYS, Unit.DAYS, [], "%0.2f")
   378ŌåÆ    (1.5, 0)
   379ŌåÆ
