   381ŌåÆ    initial value. The idea is that if we cannot use `unit`, we are forced to use a
   382ŌåÆ    lower unit, so we cannot do the division.
   383ŌåÆ
   384ŌåÆ    >>> _quotient_and_remainder(36, 24, Unit.DAYS, Unit.HOURS, [Unit.DAYS], "%0.2f")
   385ŌåÆ    (0, 36)
   386ŌåÆ
   387ŌåÆ    In other cases, return the quotient and remainder as `divmod` would do it.
   388ŌåÆ
   389ŌåÆ    >>> _quotient_and_remainder(36, 24, Unit.DAYS, Unit.HOURS, [], "%0.2f")
   390ŌåÆ    (1, 12)
   391ŌåÆ
   392ŌåÆ    """
   406ŌåÆdef _suitable_minimum_unit(min_unit: Unit, suppress: Iterable[Unit]) -> Unit:
   407ŌåÆ    """Return a minimum unit suitable that is not suppressed.
   408ŌåÆ
